{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"adff17cf-c1a1-4915-a44f-a232f0d14527","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** targeting .NET 9 — great, you have full modern MSTest support.\n\n**Recommended pattern:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via **constructor** (MSTest v3+).\n- **Sync init** — use the constructor or `[TestInitialize]`.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` returning `async Task`.\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client;\n\n    // Constructor: sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Async init runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public void Cleanup() => _client?.Dispose();\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor injection of `TestContext` replaces the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task` natively — no need for `.Result` or `.GetAwaiter()`.\n- For **class-level** async setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` with a `static async Task` method (it still takes `TestContext` as a parameter).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cea6038f-1b70-4801-b6f0-72696a988ffb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is using MSTest 3.8.2 with .NET 9. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use constructor injection — `TestContext` can be injected via the constructor.\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use the constructor or `[TestInitialize]` method.\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an `async Task` return type.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, `TestContext` can be injected via constructor DI. The old pattern of using a `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property still works but constructor injection is the modern approach.\n\n\nNow I'll provide a clear example showing how to implement this.","outputTokens":585,"requestId":"9841:3FDA7D:103BEDE:147F26E:69FFE0BE"},"id":"03fcaee3-09a3-4476-ae05-abb5142ac859","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:35:10.387Z","parentId":"40eb8b5b-a7e1-429e-9a17-457747b3a6b5"}
